using multi-threaded neighbor list subroutines
# LAMMPS Input File
# Licensed under CC BY 4.0
# A Set of Materials-Science Tutorials for the LAMMPS Simulation Package
# Modernized recreation of the MSU/CAVS tutorials by Mark A. Tschopp
# Tutorial 12, part 2 (step 1 of 2): build a solid-liquid two-phase cell of
# fcc aluminum.  A pre-existing interface removes the nucleation barrier that
# made the one-phase estimate of part 1 so uncertain.  The companion script
# velocity.lmp then reads the cell back and measures the melting point from
# the direction the interface moves.
#
# This uses the Mendelev et al. aluminum potential, which is fitted for
# liquid structure and solid-liquid coexistence and reproduces the melting
# point well.

units metal
atom_style atomic
boundary p p p
lattice fcc 4.05
Lattice spacing in x,y,z = 4.05 4.05 4.05
region box block 0 5 0 5 0 20            # square cross-section, elongated along z
create_box 1 box
Created orthogonal box = (0 0 0) to (20.25 20.25 81)
  1 by 1 by 1 MPI processor grid
create_atoms 1 box
Created 2000 atoms
  using lattice units in orthogonal box = (0 0 0) to (20.25 20.25 81)
  create_atoms CPU = 0.001 seconds
mass 1 26.98
pair_style eam/fs
pair_coeff * * Al_mm.eam.fs Al
Reading eam/fs potential file Al_mm.eam.fs with DATE: 2007-06-11
velocity all create 800.0 7654 mom yes rot yes
timestep 0.002
thermo 5000

# 1) equilibrate the whole crystal well BELOW the melting point so it stays
#    solid.  The barostat keeps the square cross-section that the cubic
#    crystal wants (x and y coupled, so they relax together) while the long
#    z axis relaxes on its own:
fix eq all npt temp 800.0 800.0 0.2 x 0.0 0.0 2.0 y 0.0 0.0 2.0 z 0.0 0.0 2.0 couple xy
run 10000
